==Dutch==

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|nl|/ˈlɛ.kər/}}
* {{audio|nl|Nl-lekker.ogg|Audio}}
* {{hyphenation|nl|lek|ker}}
* {{rhymes|nl|ɛkər|s=2}}

===Etymology 1===
From {{inh|nl|dum|lecker}}, derived from the verb {{m|dum|lekken||lick}} ({{cog|nl|likken}}). Cognate to {{cog|de|lecker}}, {{cog|af|lekker}}, {{cog|gml|lecker}}, {{cog|no|lekker}}, {{cog|sv|läcker}} and {{cog|da|lækker}}. More at [[lick]].

====Adjective====
{{nl-adj}}

# Having a nice [[taste]], [[tasty]], [[delectable]].
#: {{ux|nl|Het eten is weer '''lekker''' vandaag, mam!|The dinner is tasty again today, mum!|inline=1}}
# {{lb|nl|Netherlands}} Good, [[nice]], [[pleasant]], [[satisfying]] in a more generic sense.
#: {{ux|nl|'''Lekker''' weer!|Nice weather!|inline=1}}
#: {{ux|nl|Het badwater is '''lekker''' warm.|The bathwater is '''pleasantly''' warm.|inline=1}}
#: {{ux|nl|Ik ga zo '''lekker''' zwemmen.|I'm going for a '''nice''' swim.|inline=1}} 
# {{lb|nl|colloquial}} [[hot|Hot]], [[sexy]], physically attractive.
#: {{ux|nl|Hij is zo'n '''lekker''' ding!|He's such a '''hottie'''!|inline=1}}
#: {{ux|nl|Hé, '''lekkere''' meid!|Hey, '''sexy''' girl!|inline=1}}
# {{lb|nl|Netherlands|mainly with negative polarity}} {{l|en|healthy|Healthy}}, {{l|en|well}}, in good [[health]] {{gloss|not afflicted by illness}}.
#: {{ux|nl|Een paar minuten nadat de klas klaagde, begon de docent zich ook niet '''lekker''' te voelen.|A few minutes after the class complained, the teacher also began to feel un'''well'''.}}
# {{lb|nl|Netherlands|informal}} [[sound|Sound]] of mind, [[sane]].
#: {{ux|nl|Ben jij wel helemaal '''lekker''', gore aap?|Are you fucking '''out of your mind''', you filthy ape?}}
#: {{ux|nl|De nieuwe onderzoeksassistente is een genie, maar volgens mij is ze niet zo '''lekker''' in haar bovenkamer.|The new research assistent is a genius, but I think she's not '''mentally well''' up there?}}

=====Usage notes=====
* This adjective, especially its adverbial use, often has an ironic meaning (particularly the sense ''nice, pleasant''), e.g. ''lekker belangrijk'' or ''lekker boeiend'' for "not very important/interesting", or ''lekker type'' for "not a very pleasant person". 

